AB  - Objective: Through computerised analysis of writing ability assessment
 data, the aim was to compare the effectiveness of two generations of 
hardware smart writing devices in the application of children's writin
g performance ability from 6 to 12 years of age, and to provide data s
upport for accurate screening and assessment of those with writing dif
ficulties. Methods: A cross-sectional study was conducted to assess th
e writing performance ability of primary school students in grades 2∼6
 (a total of 555) in a primary school in Fuzhou City, Fujian Province,
 China, using the Smart Handwriting Analysis Recognition Platform (SHA
RP). The assessment indicators included writing speed, writing control
, writing integration, and time-on-paper ratio. Results: All four writ
ing assessment indicators of boys and girls performed better than the 
first generation of the second-generation smart writing device (p&lt;0
.05). Comparing the writing performance ability of students in differe
nt grades:①writing speed: except for students in grade 4, students in 
all grades and all students in grades 2∼6 performed better than one ge
neration in the second-generation intelligent writing device (p&lt;0.0
5); ②writing integration: except for students in grade 2, students in 
grades 3∼6 performed better than one generation in the second-generati
on intelligent writing device (p&lt;0.05) in terms of writing integrat
ion ability;③Writing control and time-on-paper ratio: the writing cont
rol and time-on-paper ratio of students in grades 2∼6 performed better
 in the second-generation smart writing device than in the first gener
ation (p&lt;0.05). Conclusion: ①On the second-generation smart writing
 device, the vast majority of students achieved superiority over the f
irst-generation device in the ability of all four writing assessment i
ndexes, but the differences between the two generations of the device 
in writing speed for grade 4 students and writing control for grade 2 
students did not reach the level of significance.②Writing speed, writi
ng control, writing integration, and time-on-paper ratio have key role
s in assessing overall writing performance, and can more comprehensive
ly and accurately reflect the differences in overall writing performan
ce between the two generations of intelligent writing devices. ③The si
gnificant advantages of the second-generation smart writing devices in
 improving students' writing ability also point to possible room for i
mprovement in specific grade levels or ability dimensions.
